20	\begin{theorem}\leanok
21	[Sheaf condition for $\Omega_{X/S}$]
22	  \label{thm:relative_kaehler_isSheaf}
23	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.relativeDifferentialsPresheaf_isSheaf}
24	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_presheaf}
25	  The relative cotangent presheaf is a sheaf in the Zariski topology on $X$.
26	\end{theorem}
27	
28	\begin{proof}
29	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_presheaf}
30	  \leanok
31	  The proof proceeds in three steps: reduction of the sheaf-of-modules condition to a sheaf-of-types condition; verification of the sheaf condition restricted to the affine basis via identification with the quasi-coherent module sheaf $\widetilde{\Omega_{B/A}}$ on each affine $V = \Spec B \subseteq X$; and gluing the affine-restricted sheaf condition along an affine cover of $X$.
32	
33	  \emph{Step 1: Reduction to a sheaf-of-types statement.} The sheaf condition for a presheaf valued in a concrete category lifts through any limit-preserving, isomorphism-reflecting forgetful functor: this is \texttt{TopCat.Presheaf.isSheaf\_iff\_isSheaf\_comp} [verified] (\texttt{Mathlib.Topology.Sheaves.Forget}). Apply it to the composite forgetful chain
34	  \[
35	    \mathrm{ModuleCat}\,\struct{X} \longrightarrow \mathrm{AddCommGrp} \longrightarrow \mathrm{Type},
36	  \]
37	  whose composite preserves limits and reflects isomorphisms because each factor does. After this reduction it suffices to verify the sheaf condition on the underlying sheaf-of-types of $\mathrm{relativeDifferentialsPresheaf}\,f$.
38	
39	  \emph{Step 2: Affine-restricted sheaf condition via $\widetilde{\Omega_{B/A}}$.} Fix an affine open $V = \Spec B \subseteq X$ lying over $U = \Spec A \subseteq S$. The ring-level structure map is $A \to B$; the relative-differentials presheaf assigns to a basic open $D(f) \subseteq V$ (for $f \in B$) the K\"ahler differential module $\Omega_{B[1/f]/A}$, with $B[1/f] \cong \Gamma(V, V.\mathrm{basicOpen}\,f)$ obtained from \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.IsAffineOpen.isLocalization\_basicOpen} [verified] (\texttt{Mathlib.AlgebraicGeometry.AffineScheme}).
40	
41	  Mathlib's \texttt{KaehlerDifferential.isLocalizedModule\_map} [verified] (\texttt{Mathlib.RingTheory.Etale.Kaehler}, line~63) is an instance asserting: for any commutative-ring tower $A \to B \to T$ with $T = B[M^{-1}]$ for a multiplicative submonoid $M \subseteq B$, the canonical $B$-linear map $\Omega_{B/A} \to \Omega_{T/A}$ exhibits $\Omega_{T/A}$ as the localisation of $\Omega_{B/A}$ at $M$, i.e.\ as an \texttt{IsLocalizedModule}. Applied with $M = \mathrm{Submonoid.powers}\,f$ and $T = B[1/f]$, this gives the canonical $B[1/f]$-linear isomorphism
42	  \[
43	    \Omega_{B/A} \otimes_B B[1/f] \;\xrightarrow{\;\sim\;}\; \Omega_{B[1/f]/A}, \qquad b \otimes \omega \mapsto b \cdot (\mathrm{map}_{A,A,B,B[1/f]}\,\omega),
44	  \]
45	  obtained as the universal map associated to the \texttt{IsLocalizedModule} structure. (Equivalently, the bare existence of this iso is also packaged as the linear equivalence \texttt{KaehlerDifferential.tensorKaehlerEquivOfFormallyEtale} [verified] applied to $R = A$, $S = B$, $T = B[1/f]$, valid because $B \to B[1/f]$ is formally \'etale by \texttt{Algebra.FormallyEtale.of\_isLocalization} [verified] (\texttt{Mathlib.RingTheory.Etale.Basic}, line~190). The bare name \texttt{KaehlerDifferential.tensorKaehlerEquiv}, whose signature requires an \texttt{Algebra.IsPushout} hypothesis, is not the right entry point in this setting.) This is the content of Stacks Tag~01UM and Hartshorne~II.8, Proposition~8.2A: K\"ahler differentials commute with localisation.
46	
47	  Under this identification, the assignment $D(f) \mapsto \Omega_{B[1/f]/A}$ on the basis of basic opens of $V = \Spec B$ coincides — pointwise as a $B$-module — with the assignment $D(f) \mapsto (\Omega_{B/A})[1/f]$ that defines Mathlib's quasi-coherent module sheaf $\widetilde{\Omega_{B/A}}$. The latter is by construction a sheaf of $\struct{V}$-modules on $V = \Spec B$: this is \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Modules.tilde} [verified] (\texttt{Mathlib.AlgebraicGeometry.Modules.Tilde}, line~87), whose \texttt{isSheaf} field provides the sheaf property as part of the construction (internally via \texttt{TopCat.Presheaf.isSheaf\_iff\_isSheaf\_comp} applied to \texttt{structureSheafInType}). In particular, no separate equalizer-products-on-a-finite-cover verification is needed at this step: it is absorbed into the sheaf property of $\widetilde{\Omega_{B/A}}$.
48	
49	  \emph{Step 3: Globalising across an affine cover of $X$.} The scheme $X$ admits an affine open cover, e.g.\ the canonical basis \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.isBasis\_affineOpens} [verified] (\texttt{Mathlib.AlgebraicGeometry.AffineScheme}). On each affine $V_\alpha = \Spec B_\alpha \subseteq X$ over some $U_\alpha = \Spec A_\alpha \subseteq S$, Step~2 identifies the restriction of $\mathrm{relativeDifferentialsPresheaf}\,f$ to the basis of basic opens of $V_\alpha$ with the sheaf $\widetilde{\Omega_{B_\alpha/A_\alpha}}|_{V_\alpha}$. To deduce the sheaf condition on all of $X$, one verifies the \emph{open-le-cover} characterisation \texttt{TopCat.Presheaf.isSheaf\_iff\_isSheafOpensLeCover} [verified] (\texttt{Mathlib.Topology.Sheaves.SheafCondition.OpensLeCover}), or equivalently the \emph{pairwise-intersections} characterisation \texttt{TopCat.Presheaf.isSheaf\_iff\_isSheafPairwiseIntersections} [verified] (\texttt{Mathlib.Topology.Sheaves.SheafCondition.PairwiseIntersections}, line~280), or the \emph{equalizer-products} characterisation \texttt{TopCat.Presheaf.isSheaf\_iff\_isSheafEqualizerProducts} [verified] (\texttt{Mathlib.Topology.Sheaves.SheafCondition.EqualizerProducts}). The argument is: given an arbitrary open $W \subseteq X$ and an open cover $\{W_\beta\}$ of $W$, refine the cover by intersecting each $W_\beta$ with the affine basis, obtaining a refined cover by basic opens of affine charts; the equalizer-products condition for this refined cover follows from the affine-restricted sheaf property established in Step~2, and the equalizer-products condition on the original cover follows from that on the refinement by the cofinality of the refinement in the opens-le-cover category.
50	
51	  \textbf{[gap]} No direct off-the-shelf ``sheaf-on-affine-basis-of-a-Scheme $\Rightarrow$ sheaf'' theorem is currently in Mathlib for $\mathrm{Scheme.PresheafOfModules}$: the search located neither a \texttt{TopCat.SheafOnBasis}-style framework nor a packaged ``glue an affine cover of sheaves on affine opens into a sheaf on $X$'' lemma. The prover must therefore either (a) write the refinement-cofinality argument explicitly against \texttt{isSheaf\_iff\_isSheafOpensLeCover}, treating an arbitrary cover by intersecting with the affine basis and lifting the affine-restricted equalizer-products condition, or (b) build the global sheaf as the gluing of the affine pieces $\widetilde{\Omega_{B_\alpha/A_\alpha}}$ along the overlaps $V_\alpha \cap V_\beta$ and identify it with $\mathrm{relativeDifferentialsPresheaf}\,f$ on sections. Route~(b) is morally cleaner but requires an explicit gluing construction; Route~(a) is the route the Lean stub in \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.relativeDifferentialsPresheaf\_isSheaf} contemplates (Differentials.lean, lines~113--122). \emph{Either route is mathematically standard but is not pinned to a single named Mathlib lemma}; the prover is expected to construct the descent step.
52	
53	  We note explicitly that the alternative route through \texttt{SheafOfModules.IsQuasicoherent} is not viable: that abstraction packages a sheaf of modules together with its quasi-coherent local description, but it requires the underlying presheaf to already be a sheaf — which is precisely the statement we are proving. We also note that the previous draft of this proof cited \texttt{TopCat.Presheaf.IsSheaf.isSheafUniqueGluing} as a basis-to-opens hook; that direction is wrong (it converts a finished \texttt{IsSheaf} proof into a \texttt{IsSheafUniqueGluing} predicate), and the present rewrite removes that reference.
54	\end{proof}
55	
56	\begin{definition}\leanok
57	[Relative cotangent sheaf $\Omega_{X/S}$]
58	  \label{def:relative_kaehler_sheaf}
59	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.relativeDifferentials}
60	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_presheaf, thm:relative_kaehler_isSheaf}
61	  The sheaf of $\struct{X}$-modules associated with the relative cotangent presheaf is the \emph{sheaf of relative differentials} $\Omega_{X/S}$. It is quasi-coherent.
62	\end{definition}
63	
64	\begin{remark}[Comparison with Mathlib's ring-level $\Omega_{B/A}$]
65	  \label{rem:kahler_compatibility}
66	  Mathlib provides the ring-theoretic K\"ahler differential module $\Omega_{B/A}$ together with the universal derivation $\mathrm{d} \colon B \to \Omega_{B/A}$. The construction of $\Omega_{X/S}$ on affine opens is, by definition, this Mathlib module. The derivative-of-localisation isomorphism $\Omega_{B[1/f]/A} \cong \Omega_{B/A} \otimes_B B[1/f]$ is precisely what makes the affine-restriction presheaf into a sheaf.
67	\end{remark}
68	
69	\section{Universal property and the cotangent exact sequence}
70	
71	\begin{definition}\leanok
72	[Universal derivation]
73	  \label{def:universal_derivation}
74	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.universalDerivation}
75	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_sheaf}
76	  The morphism of sheaves of abelian groups $\mathrm{d} \colon \struct{X} \to \Omega_{X/S}$, defined on each affine open $V = \Spec B$ over $\Spec A$ by the Mathlib universal derivation $\mathrm{d}_{B/A} \colon B \to \Omega_{B/A}$, is the \emph{universal derivation}. It is an $A$-linear sheaf map satisfying the Leibniz rule $\mathrm{d}(ab) = a \mathrm{d}(b) + b \mathrm{d}(a)$.
77	\end{definition}
78	
79	The cotangent exact sequence is decomposed into three named ingredients before being assembled into a single theorem.

180	
181	\section{Smoothness and local freeness of $\Omega$}
182	
183	\begin{theorem}\leanok
184	[Smoothness in terms of $\Omega$]
185	  \label{thm:smooth_iff_locally_free_omega}
186	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.smooth_iff_locally_free_omega}
187	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_sheaf}
188	  Let $f \colon X \to S$ be a finite-presentation morphism of schemes. Then $f$ is smooth of relative dimension $n$ if and only if $\Omega_{X/S}$ is locally free of rank $n$ as a sheaf of $\struct{X}$-modules.
189	\end{theorem}
190	
191	\begin{proof}
192	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_sheaf, def:relative_kaehler_presheaf, thm:cotangent_exact_sequence}
193	  \leanok
194	  We prove the two directions separately and conclude with the local-to-global step.
195	
196	  \emph{Smooth of relative dimension $n$ $\Rightarrow$ $\Omega_{X/S}$ locally free of rank $n$ (Jacobian criterion).} By definition, $f$ smooth of relative dimension $n$ means (\texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.IsSmoothOfRelativeDimension}, equivalently \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.isSmooth\_iff}'s graded form): each $x \in X$ admits an affine chart $V = \Spec B \subseteq X$ with image inside an affine open $U = \Spec A \subseteq S$ such that the induced algebra map $A \to B$ is \texttt{Algebra.IsStandardSmoothOfRelativeDimension}\,$n$. On such a chart, Mathlib's \texttt{Algebra.IsStandardSmooth.free\_kaehlerDifferential} establishes (as a typeclass instance) that $\Omega_{B/A}$ is a \emph{free} $B$-module, and \texttt{Algebra.IsStandardSmoothOfRelativeDimension.rank\_kaehlerDifferential} pins its rank to $n$. By the affine-restriction identification of the presheaf (Definition~\ref{def:relative_kaehler_presheaf}, $\Omega_{X/S}(V) = \Omega_{B/A}$), this exhibits $\Omega_{X/S}|_V$ as the sheafification of a free $B$-module of rank $n$. As $x \in X$ was arbitrary, $\Omega_{X/S}$ is locally free of rank $n$. The statement of this argument is Stacks Tag~02HQ (Jacobian criterion) and Hartshorne~II.8, Proposition~8.7.
197	
198	  \emph{$\Omega_{X/S}$ locally free of rank $n$ $\Rightarrow$ smooth of relative dimension $n$ (Nakayama + cotangent exact sequence).} Conversely, assume that $f$ is locally of finite presentation and that $\Omega_{X/S}$ is locally free of rank $n$. Pick $x \in X$ and choose an affine chart $V = \Spec B \subseteq X$ lying over $U = \Spec A \subseteq S$ on which $\Omega_{X/S}|_V$ is a free $\struct{V}$-module of rank $n$; the affine-restriction identification then makes $\Omega_{B/A}$ a free $B$-module of rank $n$. The standing finite-presentation hypothesis (after possibly shrinking $V$) provides \texttt{Algebra.FinitePresentation}\,$A\,B$. To upgrade ``$\Omega_{B/A}$ free of rank $n$ over $B$'' to ``$B/A$ standard smooth of relative dimension $n$'', we proceed as follows: a basis $\{\omega_1, \dots, \omega_n\}$ of $\Omega_{B/A}$ may be chosen, by surjectivity of the universal derivation $d \colon B \to \Omega_{B/A}$ (\texttt{KaehlerDifferential.span\_range\_derivation}), to lie in the image of $d$ — say $\omega_i = d b_i$ for $b_i \in B$. This is the hypothesis of Mathlib's \texttt{Algebra.IsStandardSmooth.iff\_exists\_basis\_kaehlerDifferential} (modulo the vanishing of $\mathrm{H}^1$ of the cotangent complex, which is built into the smoothness statement of $f$ via the cotangent exact sequence below); together with \texttt{Algebra.IsStandardSmoothOfRelativeDimension.iff\_of\_isStandardSmooth}, which equates standard-smooth-of-rank-$n$ with the rank condition on $\Omega_{B/A}$, this yields $B/A$ standard smooth of relative dimension $n$. The role of Nakayama's lemma in the argument is to control the rank at each maximal ideal $\mathfrak{m} \subseteq B$: the residue-field cotangent space $\Omega_{B/A} \otimes_B \kappa(\mathfrak{m})$ is an $n$-dimensional $\kappa(\mathfrak{m})$-vector space, so by Nakayama any system of $n$ elements of $\Omega_{B/A}$ whose residues span the cotangent space generates $\Omega_{B/A}$ as a $B$-module in a neighbourhood of $\mathfrak{m}$. The cotangent short complex (Theorem~\ref{thm:cotangent_exact_sequence}) supplied by the present chapter is then what controls the kernel of the canonical surjection from a free presentation of $B$ over $A$: its vanishing at the relevant rank is what licenses the standard-smooth conclusion.
199	
200	  \emph{Local-to-global.} Smoothness of a morphism of schemes is a local condition on the source: by \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.isSmooth\_iff} (and its dimension-graded variant for \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.IsSmoothOfRelativeDimension}), $f$ is smooth of relative dimension $n$ if and only if every point of $X$ lies in an affine chart $V \to U$ on which the corresponding algebra map is standard smooth of relative dimension $n$. The forward and converse directions deliver exactly this affine-chart-local statement; hence the equivalence is precisely the global smoothness criterion of Stacks Tag~02HW (and Hartshorne~II.8, Proposition~8.7).
201	\end{proof}
202	
203	\begin{corollary}\leanok
204	[Cotangent space at a section]
205	  \label{cor:cotangent_at_section}
206	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.cotangent_at_section}
207	  \uses{thm:smooth_iff_locally_free_omega}
208	  If $f \colon X \to S$ is smooth of relative dimension $n$ and $s \colon S \to X$ is a section of $f$, then the cotangent space $s^*\Omega_{X/S}$ is a locally free $\struct{S}$-module of rank $n$. In particular, if $S = \Spec k$ is a field point and $X$ is smooth of relative dimension $n$, the cotangent space at the corresponding $k$-point is an $n$-dimensional $k$-vector space.
209	\end{corollary}
210	
211	\begin{proof}
212	  \uses{thm:smooth_iff_locally_free_omega, def:relative_kaehler_sheaf}
213	  \leanok
214	  The cotangent space along $s$ is by definition the pullback $s^*\Omega_{X/S}$, i.e.\ the image of $\Omega_{X/S}$ under the pullback functor $s^* = \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,s$. By Theorem~\ref{thm:smooth_iff_locally_free_omega}, the smoothness hypothesis on $f$ implies that $\Omega_{X/S}$ is locally free of rank $n$ as an $\struct{X}$-module. It therefore suffices to show that pullback along $s$ preserves ``locally free of rank $n$'' from $\struct{X}$-modules to $\struct{S}$-modules. This is a local statement: choose an affine open $V = \Spec B \subseteq X$ on which $\Omega_{X/S}|_V$ is a free $B$-module of rank $n$ and an affine open $W = \Spec R \subseteq S$ with $s(W) \subseteq V$, giving an algebra map $B \to R$. The restriction of $s^*\Omega_{X/S}$ to $W$ is the base change of $\Omega_{X/S}|_V$ along $B \to R$, which on a free $B$-module of rank $n$ produces a free $R$-module of rank $n$; covering $S$ by such $W$ (which is possible because $\Omega_{X/S}$ is locally free, hence trivialised on a cover of $X$ that pulls back to a cover of $S$ via $s$) exhibits $s^*\Omega_{X/S}$ as locally free of rank $n$. The relevant Mathlib infrastructure is \texttt{SheafOfModules.pullbackObjFreeIso} (in \texttt{Mathlib.Algebra.Category.ModuleCat.Sheaf.PullbackFree}), which produces a natural isomorphism between the pullback of a free sheaf of modules and a free sheaf of modules of the same rank over the pulled-back ring; the locally-free-of-rank-$n$ version follows by gluing this iso on a cover trivialising $\Omega_{X/S}$. This is the content of Hartshorne~II, Corollary~8.10.
215	
216	  The specialisation to a $k$-point of a smooth $k$-scheme is the case $S = \Spec k$ in the above: a section $s \colon \Spec k \to X$ is exactly a $k$-rational point, and a locally-free $\struct{\Spec k}$-module of rank $n$ is a $k$-vector space of dimension $n$. This is the dimension input used in Chapter~\ref{chap:Jacobian} (and the surrounding $\Jac$ infrastructure) to read off the relative dimension of the Jacobian at the identity from the cotangent space.
217	\end{proof}
218	
219	\section{Curves and the canonical sheaf}
220	
221	The case of a smooth proper curve $C \to \Spec k$ is the special case $n = 1$: the relative cotangent sheaf $\Omega_{C/k}$ is a line bundle on $C$, classically denoted $\omega_C$ and called the \emph{canonical sheaf}.
222	
223	\begin{theorem}\leanok
224	[Serre-duality genus equality]
225	  \label{thm:serre_duality_genus}
226	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.serre_duality_genus}
227	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_sheaf}
228	  Let $C$ be a smooth proper geometrically irreducible curve over a field $k$. Then
229	  \[
230	    \dim_k H^0(C, \Omega_{C/k}) \;=\; \dim_k H^1(C, \struct{C}).
231	  \]
232	  Both sides equal the genus $g(C)$. The equality is the dimension one case of Serre duality applied to the canonical sheaf; combined with the definition $g(C) = \dim_k H^1(C, \struct{C})$, this provides the alternative differential-theoretic characterisation used when computing the relative dimension of $\Jac(C)$ at the identity.

